tags.description:
Elorus supports interacting with the [notifications](#tag/notifications) and 
[time entries](#tag/timeentries) resources through websockets. 
A subset of those resources' actions is supported.
Only `wss` (secure websockets) scheme is supported. 
To open a websocket connection you have to own a valid Oauth2 token.
Please refer to the [Authentication](#section/Authentication) section to 
find out how to obtain one. 
In order to open a websocket connection you must include the `Authorization` 
and `X-Elorus-Organization` headers on the connect request.

Example using `wsta`:

    wsta --header Authorization:"Bearer <the_access_token>" \
         --header X-Elorus-Organization:<organization_id> \
         wss://api.elorus.com/ws/native/ 

Elorus uses multiplexing, so you must use one websocket per client.
That means that, you shouldn't open a new websocket for each request or 
resource you want to interact with.
The `stream` key must be included on each request.
The supported streams are: `notifications` and `timeentries`.
The request data must be JSON encoded. The responses are also JSON encoded.
Elorus recognizes the following request format:

    {
        "stream": <stream_name>,
        "payload": {
            "action": <action_name>,
            "resource_id": <resource_id_if_applicable>
        }
    }

The responses have the following format:

    {
        "stream": <stream_name>,
        "payload": {
            "action": <action_name>,
            "data": <response_data>,
            "resource_id": <resource_id_or_null>,
            "status": <http_status_code>
        }
    }

In case of erroneous responses the `data` and `status` entries will contain 
info about the error.
If the data sent do not follow the request format described above, a response
will be sent informing the user about what went wrong.
That response will have the following format:

    {
        "error": <error_message>
    }

Finally, please note that responses might be received at any time without a 
client's request, due to another client's action.


# notifications

All the responses will include a list of all the notifications. The format is 
the same as [here](#operation/notifications_list).

## Available actions are:

### list
Request:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "list"
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "list",
            "data": <paginated_list_of_results>,
            "status": <http_status_code>,
            "resource_id": null
        }
    }

### destroy
Request:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "destroy",
            "resource_id": <notification_id>
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "destroy",
            "resource_id": <notification_id>,
            "data": <paginated_list_of_results>,
            "status": <http_status_code>
        }
    }

### mark_read
Request:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "mark_read",
            "resource_id": <notification_id>
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "mark_read",
            "resource_id": <notification_id>,
            "data": <paginated_list_of_results>,
            "status": <http_status_code>
        }
    }

### bulk_mark_read
Request:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "bulk_mark_read"
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "bulk_mark_read",
            "data": <paginated_list_of_results>,
            "status": <http_status_code>,
            "resource_id": null
        }
    }


## Push events:

The server may push the following events:

### new
A new notification has been created. 
Info about the new notification is not included in the response data. 
It's up to the application to refresh its notifications' list.

Response:

    {
        "stream": "notifications",
        "payload": {
            "action": "new",
        }
    }

### destroy

Sent data match the `destroy` action response above. 

### mark_read

Sent data match the `mark_read` action response above.

### bulk_mark_read

Sent data match the `bulk_mark_read` action response above.


# timeentries

## Available actions are:

### start
Start a time entry.

Request:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "start"
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "start",
            "data": <response_data>,
            "status": <http_status_code>,
            "resource_id": null
        }
    }

The response_data format is the same as [here](#operation/timeentries_start)

### ongoing
Get the ongoing time entry.

Request:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "ongoing"
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "ongoing",
            "data": <response_data>,
            "status": <http_status_code>,
            "resource_id": null
        }
    }

The response_data format is the same as [here](#operation/timeentries_ongoing)

### stop
Stop the currently running time entry.

Request:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "stop"
        }
    }

Response:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "stop",
            "data": <response_data>,
            "status": <http_status_code>,
            "resource_id": null
        }
    }

The response_data format is the same as [here](#operation/timeentries_stop)

### update
Update a time entry.

Request:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "update",
            "resource_id": <timeentry_id>,
            "data": <request_data>
        }
    }

The request_data format is the same as [here](#operation/timeentries_update)

Response:

    {
        "stream": "timeentries",
        "payload": {
            "action": "update",
            "data": <response_data>,
            "status": <http_status_code>,
            "resource_id": <timeentry_id>
        }
    }

The response_data format is the same as [here](#operation/timeentries_update)


## Push events:

The server may push the start, stop and update events. Sent data match
the corresponding action responses above.
